Executive summary
  
Retention is a major engine of the business. Across 2,520 unique attendees, 1,352 are repeat attendees and 1,168 are one-time attendees, which means 53.7% of attendees return after their first class. Put differently, the audience is slightly more repeat than one-time by headcount, which is a strong retention foundation.

Repeat attendees drive a disproportionate share of the business. While they represent 53.7% of unique attendees, they account for 79.8% of registrations and 81.6% of revenue. That indicates the model depends heavily on getting people back for additional classes, and that repeat customers are materially more valuable than one-time attendees.

Loyalty also runs fairly deep. Based on the visit-frequency distribution, 779 attendees registered exactly twice, 222 registered three times, 188 registered 4–5 times, and 163 registered 6+ times. Using the total registration count, repeat attendees average about 3.4 registrations per repeat attendee, and about 13.9% of all attendees have registered 4+ times. That points to a meaningful core of highly engaged customers, not just a thin layer of second visits.

The strongest first experiences for driving future attendance are concentrated in a few subcategories. On raw conversion rate, Science (100%), Fiber Arts (99.5%), and Wellness (87.0%) lead. Among categories with meaningful scale, Wellness stands out most clearly, while Art is the largest entry-point cohort by far (1,237 attendees) and converts 47.7% of them into repeat attendees, making it the single biggest feeder into the repeat base. By contrast, Outdoor Education (28.6%) and Culinary (19.3%) appear much weaker as first-touch conversion channels.
                                                                                                                                                                                           
People do not typically come back immediately. The boxplot suggests a median of roughly 130 days to second registration, with a wide spread across returning attendees. Many people come back within the first few months, but there is also a long tail stretching well beyond a year, which implies retention should be viewed as both a near-term rebooking opportunity and a longer-term reactivation opportunity.
                                                                                                                                                                                           
Cohort performance also suggests retention has strengthened in many more recent cohorts, though monthly results are somewhat uneven. Several 2024 and 2025 entry cohorts post return rates in the 60%–80%+ range, indicating that when the first experience lands well, later attendance can be very strong. Overall, the picture is clear: repeat behavior is not marginal here — it is central to both volume and revenue.
                                                                                                                                                                                           
                                                                                                                                                                                           
Board-style summary

- Retention is strong: 53.7% of attendees return, with 1,352 repeat attendees out of 2,520 unique attendees.
- Repeat customers drive the business: they generate 79.8% of registrations and 81.6% of revenue.
- Loyalty has real depth: repeat attendees average about 3.4 registrations each, and roughly 14% of all attendees have attended 4+ times.
- Best first experiences for future conversion: Wellness is the strongest scaled entry point; Science and Fiber Arts have the highest repeat rates but smaller cohorts; Art is the largest feeder into the repeat base.
- Return timing is moderate, not immediate: the median time to a second registration is about 130 days, with a long tail.                                                                                                                                                                                           
                                                                                                                                                                                  